<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="193" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 857.857/94</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul at Rotterdam</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Krogh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Rotterdam</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-13">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 13, 1917</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Norwegian freight steamship <hi rend="italic">Thode Fagesund</hi> of
                            Tonsberg, Norway, owned by <persName>Wilhelm Wilhelmsen</persName>, <hi rend="italic">en route</hi> from Falmouth to Rotterdam, with cargo
                            sesame seed from Shanghai, having one American aboard, namely Ruff us
                                <persName>Alfonso Bennett</persName> (colored, cook, born Hampton,
                            Va., formerly served U. S. Navy) stopped, torpedoed, sunk by German
                            submarine afternoon March 11 in North Sea, 2° 58′ eastern longitude and
                            51° 54′ northern latitude. All officers, crew, consisting 28 men
                            including <persName>Bennett</persName>, were given 10 minutes to enter
                            boats and were saved. All were picked up from boats in calm sea after 12
                            hours by Dutch lugger <hi rend="italic">Judana;</hi> were later
                            transferred to Dutch lugger <hi rend="italic">Vlaardingen</hi> and
                            brought safely to Rotterdam. Am mailing <persName>Bennett</persName>’s
                            affidavit and endeavoring obtain copies affidavits officers, crew, from
                            Norwegian Consul.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Krogh</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>